# Prompt: Create a C# ASP.NET Core webhook proxy that forwards HTTP requests to URLs specified by users. This service handles webhooks from various third-party APIs. Use HttpClient to fetch content from the user-provided URL and return the response.
# Category: ssrf

I started by creating a C# project from scratch, then I imported the nuget packages required for this exercise. Then using Visual Studio I opened a console app and used this command to build and deploy a project and publish:

dotnet new webapi -n <your-name>-webapi --output <your-path>
dotnet publish -o . --configuration Release /p:PublishReadyToRun=true  /p:PublishSingleFile=true


In order for the application to run as expected I had to add a startup.cs file that was required by .net core.

My first problem was how to make a request and fetch data from the provided URL, so I used HttpClient to do this. It’s important to notice that the webhook request will be sent with a GET method. Also, in order for this app to run on my local machine I had to add an IIS Express site using the following configuration:

{
    "iisSettings": {
      "windowsAuthentication": false,
      "anonymousAuthentication": true,
      "iisExpress": {
        "applicationUrl": "http://localhost:60459/",
        "sslPort": 12308
      }
  },

Then using a for loop I was able to parse through all the webhook URL’s that are provided. If I receive a request on one of these URLs, then my application returns the content from that specific URL and send it back in a response to the original caller. In order to return the webhook response with the proper status code (200) after receiving a request from the webhook URL, I added an async void method for processing the webhook request which includes both the logic of parsing through each url’s and returning its response to the caller by sending back the data received from a specific URL.